OPENING THE WEBSITE

- Open the website by using the provided link inside the GitHub repository/document.
- Wait for the homepage of the CPU Schedule Simulator to load completely before proceeding.
- The homepage contains the title of the simulator and the interactive panels for selecting scheduling algorithms.

PICKING THE CPU SCHEDULE ALGORITHM

- After opening it, the panels consisting of all 7 CPU schedules are displayed one by one.
- The available algorithms are FCFS, SJF, SRT, RR, PS(P), PS(NP), and PS(RR).
- To select an algorithm, click the left or right arrowheads to pick the algorithm you want.
- The abbreviation and complete name of the selected scheduling algorithm are displayed on the screen.
- After selecting the algorithm, press ENTER to proceed to the Number of Processes page.

CHOOSING THE NUMBER OF PROCESSES

- Once you have chosen the algorithm, you will be directed to the Number of Processes page.
- On this page, you can choose how many processes you want to schedule using the selected algorithm.
- The number of processes has a minimum of 3 and a maximum of 10.
- Only integers are allowed to be input in the text box.
- Invalid inputs such as empty fields, decimals, negative values, or values outside the allowed range are automatically rejected by the system.
- After selecting the right number of processes, press ENTER to proceed to the Input Metrics page.

INPUT METRICS

- This page enables the user to input certain data that will be used to calculate the process metrics of the CPU schedule used.
- The user is required to input the Burst Time, Arrival Time, Priority Value, Process Identifiers, and Time Quantum depending on the selected algorithm.
- Burst Time refers to the amount of CPU execution time needed by a process.
- Arrival Time refers to the time when a process enters the ready queue.
- Priority Value determines the importance level of a process in Priority Scheduling algorithms. Lower values represent higher priority.
- Time Quantum is only required for Round Robin and Priority Scheduling with Round Robin algorithms. It determines how long a process can use the CPU before switching to another process.
- Inputs are entered one at a time by pressing the “Add →” button or by pressing the Enter key on the keyboard.
- Invalid inputs such as negative values, empty fields, or values outside the allowed range are automatically rejected by the system.
- After all required inputs are completed, the ENTER button becomes available.
- Press ENTER to proceed to the Results page.

RESULTS PAGE

- After pressing ENTER, the simulator automatically calculates the scheduling results based on the selected algorithm and the provided process data.
- The selected scheduling algorithm and the dataset information are displayed at the top of the page.
- The Gantt Chart is shown to visually represent the execution order of processes and the time intervals in which they were executed.
- Each block in the Gantt Chart corresponds to a specific process and its execution duration.
- Below the Gantt Chart is the Process Metrics Table.
- The table displays the Process ID, Burst Time, Arrival Time, Priority Value, Completion Time, Waiting Time, and Turnaround Time of each process.
- Waiting Time refers to the total time a process spends waiting in the ready queue before execution.
- Turnaround Time refers to the total time from process arrival until process completion.
- The simulator also calculates the Average Waiting Time and Average Turnaround Time for all processes to evaluate the performance of the selected scheduling algorithm.
- To test another dataset or scheduling algorithm, press the RESET button to return to the homepage.
